Key Match Events: Wembanyama limped to the locker room after injuring his foot and struggled to make an impact, ending with a career-low six points.
The Thunder took advantage, with Holmgren scoring seven points during a 14-7 run to help Oklahoma City stretch its lead to 42-26 at the 7:15 mark of the second quarter.
Oklahoma City led by 19 in the first half and maintained a double-digit cushion, leading by 19 in the third quarter.
A 9-2 Oklahoma City run put the hosts in control once again.
San Antonio pulled within 82-75 with 10:23 left in the fourth but couldn't catch up.
Post-Match Reflections: The Thunder's victory kept their undefeated streak intact, and they have led by 19 in the first half and maintained a double-digit cushion.
The Thunder and the Cleveland Cavaliers are the only undefeated teams in the league after Boston's loss at Indiana.
Miscellaneous Highlights: Wembanyama didn't attempt a single shot in the second half.
The Thunder made a season-high 17 three-pointers, including 13 before halftime.
Oklahoma City also tallied a season-best 28 assists.
